definition.value: A person who identifies as X-gender.

Someone whose gender identity is only partly male, regardless of their assigned gender at birth. They may or may not identify as another gender in addition to feeling partially a boy or man. They may also define their identity as both male and genderless (agender).

A person having a gender identity which is partially, but not wholly, female or feminine, whatever their assigned gender at birth. They may or may not identify as another gender in addition to feeling partially a girl or woman.
A form of physical intimacy that can be directed to reproduction (one possible goal of sexual intercourse) and/or to enjoying the body of someone else; activities associated with sexual intercourse.

Totality of normal and abnormal, conscious and unconscious, overt and covert sensations, thoughts, feelings, and actions related to sexual organs and other erotogenic zones, including goals and techniques.
The sexual functions, activities, attitudes, and orientations of an individual.
The sexual functions, activities, attitudes, and orientations of an individual animal.
The sexual functions and activities observed in plants.
The sexual functions, activities, attitudes, and orientations of an individual bird.
The sexual functions, activities, attitudes, and orientations of an individual mammal.
The sexual functions, activities, attitudes, and orientations of an individual human being.
Sexual behavior, both reproductively and non-reproductively motivated, observed in members of the kingdom Animalia.
The sexual functions, activities, attitudes, and orientations of an individual primate.
Sexual behavior, both reproductively and non-reproductively motivated, observed in members of the class Mammalia.
Sexual behavior, both reproductively and non-reproductively motivated, observed in primates.
Sexual activities of humans.
Sexual behavior, both reproductively and non-reproductively motivated, observed in humans.
The treatment of mental conditions by physical means rather than psychotherapy.
The observable response a mammal makes to any situation.
The observable response a primate makes to any situation.

Human behavior is the responses of individuals or groups of humans to internal and external stimuli. It refers to the array of every physical action and observable emotion associated with individuals, as well as the human race.
The observable response a human makes to any situation.
Human behaviors related to or involving clothing.
Behaviors generally considered acceptable, appropriate, or desirable for people based on their actual or perceived gender or sex. These behaviors may vary significantly from culture to culture.
Some scholars have argued that gender persists in non-human animals, although there is no consensus on this subject.
Behavior related to ascribed gender roles.
Convulsions induced in order to treat mental conditions. It is used primarily in the treatment of severe affective disorders and schizophrenia.
Subjects exhibit greater than the normal level of domineering, assertive posturing and/or hostile physical action toward partners while mating.
A social behavior that can potentially cause or threaten physical or emotional harm.
An aggressive social behavior that involves one bullying another.
An aggressive social behavior that involves violent actions among individuals.
Any action that results in intimidation, harm, damage, or destruction of someone or something.
Social behaviors in animals.
Social interactions that occur between two or more individual animals, usually of the same species.
Social behaviors in mammals.
Social behaviors in primates.
Social behaviors in humans.
Behavior which is abusive or considered abuse.
Abusive behavior in which the abuser feels no concern about their victim(s).

Actions that harm or lack consideration for the well-being of others. It has also been defined as any type of conduct that violates the basic rights of another person and any behaviour that is considered to be disruptive to others in society.

A procedure in which a series of short duration electric currents are passed via electrodes through the brain to cause a controlled seizure for the purpose of treating severe, intractable forms of mental conditions, including depression, mania, and catatonia.
Electrically induced convulsions primarily used in the treatment of severe affective disorders and schizophrenia.

Use of electroconvulsive therapy has been considered extremely controversial due in part to its crude, early, and involuntary usage in asylums. Additionally, electroconvulsive therapy has been, mostly historically, used in attempts to painfully "convert" gay persons to heterosexuality and transgender persons to being cisgender (despite a lack of evidence of the possibility or efficacy of such a process).
Anatomical structure which is the aggregate material substance of an individual member of the class Mammalia.
Anatomical structure which is the aggregate material substance of an individual member of the order Primates.
Electroconvulsive therapy which is administered against a person's will or otherwise without their consent.
Digestive system in mammals.
Digestive system in primates.
Digestive system in humans.
A reproductive organ which serves to provide wolffian gametes (sperm).
The penis, as observed in mammals.
The penis, as observed in select vertebrate species.
The penis, as observed in primates.
The penis, as observed in humans.

A vital record that documents the birth of a child. The term "birth certificate" can refer to either the original document certifying the circumstances of the birth or to a certified copy of or representation of the ensuing registration of that birth. Depending on the jurisdiction, a record of birth might or might not contain verification of the event by such as a midwife or doctor.

Note that not all jurisdictions issue birth certificates. Sweden, for instance, no longer issues birth certificates. Instead, the Swedish Tax Agency will issue a Personbevis (Extract from the Population Register) for individuals born in Sweden. This takes the place of both birth and marriage certificates for international purposes. In England and Wales, "birth certificate" refers to a certified copy of an entry in the birth register, rather than a separate document.
Medical patients who are LGBTQIA+.
The genital system that creates, maintains, or otherwise harbors müllerian gametes (oocytes, eggs).
The genital system that creates, maintains, or otherwise harbors wolffian gametes (spermatozoa, sperm).
